[The state of Washington is now issuing reports. The number of cases is now based on confirmed cases and is likely to increase as more are confirmed. - Mod.LL]

******
[2]
Date: Fri 8 May 2015
Source: King 5 News [edited]
http://www.king5.com/story/news/local/2015/05/08/e-coli-lynden-milk-makers-festival-whatcom-county/27012919/


The family of a Lynden teenager is looking for answers after he contracted _E. coli_ leading to kidney failure. The Whatcom County Health Department is trying to figure out what caused he and 44 others to fall ill after a dairy festival in Lynden.

The teenager described how he helped set up a maze in this dairy barn before the Milk Makers Fest in April 2015. "We were to pick up hay bales and set them up in a certain way for a map for a maze," he said. As a reward for their work, he and the rest of the Lynden High School Ag Tech class were fed donuts in the very same barn. He said the hand washing stations were not turned on. He found only a pump of hand sanitizer.

"Just the one hand sanitizing station that was on a pole that, as I said before, was empty," he said. The next day the 15-year-old fell ill.

"He came home from school and complained he had a really bad headache," said his mother. Soon he passed blood and started vomiting. Finally in the hospital doctors told his family he had contracted _E. coli_.

